UML:TaggedValue.value: The value of the speed limit event.
The name of an instance of the SpeedLimitEvent class.
The vehicle type an instance of the SpeedLimitEvent class applies to.
The period in which this attribute event is valid.

The type LR_DirectedEdge includes any one-dimensional topology of type Edge::DirectedEdge from ISO 19107 that can be linearly measured, that is, that realizes the ILinearElement interface. Directed edges typically have one or more weights associated with them instead of having a length. Measuring along a directed edge, therefore, entails prorating a weight value. Consequently, the Linear Referencing Method of choice is typically of the interpolative type and unlikely to be of the relative type.
The "DirectedEdge" type implements the DirectedEdge interface from ISO 19107 and the ILinearElement interface.
The name of an instance of the DirectedEdge class.
The type "Road" extends Feature and implements the ILinearElement interface.
The name of an instance of the Road class.
The centerline geometry of an instance of the Road class.
The height attribute of a WildlifeFence.
The "Track" type extends Feature, implementing the ILinearElement interface.
The centerline geometry of an instance of the Track class.
The name of an instance of the Track class.
The type LR_Feature includes any feature that can be linearly measured, that is, any feature that realizes the ILinearElement interface.

The type LR_Curve shall include any one-dimensional geometry of type Geometry::Curve as specified in ISO 19107, that can be linearly measured, that is, that realizes the ILinearElement interface. The LR_Curve also realizes the ISpatial interface. This allows spatial positions to be projected onto the LR_Curve to determine a corresponding linearly referenced location along the curve and vice versa.
The abstract Feature class from which LR_Feature is subtyped is the root class for all features.
The union LinearElementType provides a choice for specifying the underlying linear element upon which the measures in the Linear Referencing System are made.
a Feature instance that realizes the ILinearElement and IFeature interfaces
a Curve instance that realizes the ILinearElement and ISpatial interfaces
a Directed-edge instance that realizes the ILinearElement interface.

PositionExpression is used to fully describe a linearly referenced location given by the linear element being measured, the method of measurement and a measure value specified with a distance expression.
In situations where the first two values (linear element and measurement method) are known or can be implied, it is sufficient to specify only a distance expression in order to describe the linearly referenced location.
The type ReferentType is used to describe the type of referent.

The referent is a reference marker typically located in the right of way of the road, rail or other transportation system. Usually reference markers are initially spaced at a uniform distance along the linear element being measured, though subsequent re-alignments can result in uneven spacing between the markers. Specifying their location with a relative Linear Referencing Method a distance from the preceding marker minimizes the impact of such changes.

The referent is the location of an intersection specified by the referent name. The intersection location is typically taken as the location of the intersection of the reference lines of the streets comprising the intersection and is, therefore, not necessarily precise or deterministic. Physical markers may be installed to remedy this. The Linear Referencing System should include specific rules about how intersection locations are determined if this type of referent is permitted.

The referent represents where an administrative or maintenance boundary crosses the linear element being measured. This is typically the first time the boundary crosses the linear element. If the boundary runs along the linear element, it would be the point at which they first become collinear. The Linear Referencing System should include specific rules about how boundaries are handled if this type of referent is permitted. If the linear element changes at the boundary as for a county route beginning at the county boundary, then the Linear Referencing method is more correctly categorized as absolute.
The referent is the location of a physical landmark visible in the field.
The enumeration LRMType specifies the allowable types for the Linear Referencing Method.
absolute (e.g. milepoint, kilometre-point in Annex C) measurements are made from the start of the linear element being measured, in the direction of the linear element

relative (e.g. kilometre-post, milepost, reference post, county milepoint in Annex C) measurements are made from the specified from referent location, in the direction of the linear element unless overridden by a towards referent, in which case the direction is from the from referent towards the towards referent
interpolative (e.g. percentage, normalized in Annex C) measurements are interpolated in accordance with the default length of the linear element
For from and towards referents, the type Referent is used to specify a known location along the LinearElement.
The attribute name is the identifier used for this referent.
The attribute type is the type of this referent.
The optional attribute position is the spatial position of this referent, given in some coordinate system.
The optional attribute location is the location of this referent given as a linearly referenced location along the feature that owns the referent

The optional attribute restartValue is the measure value at the location of this referent for the specified Linear Referencing Method. This measure value is a new start value for measurements made from this referent.
LinearElement specifies the underlying linear element upon which the measures in the Linear Referencing System are made.
The attribute linearElement specifies the linear element along which measurements are made.

DistanceExpression specifies the linear referenced measure value. This shall include the distance measured along the linear element. If the Linear Referencing Method LRMType is relative, the distance expression may also include an along referent to specify where the measuring begins. Otherwise, measuring begins at the start of the linear element. Measuring is in the direction of the linear element, unless a towards referent is provided.

The attribute distanceAlong gives a measure (usually a distance) of this distance expression. If the Linear Referencing Method is of type absolute, the distance is measured from the start of the linear element. If relative, it is measured from the along referent's from referent. If interpolative, it is based on the default length or weight of the linear element.
The enumeration DistanceAlongDirection gives the options for positive direction along the linear element being measured. The values are same and opposite.
Same direction as the linear element.
Opposite direction as the linear element.
LinearReferencingMethod describes the manner in which measurements are made along (and optionally offset from) a linear element.
The attribute name gives the name of this Linear Referencing Method, such as kilometre-point.
The attribute type gives the type of this Linear Referencing Method.
The attribute units specifies the units of measure used by this Linear Referencing Method for measures along the linear element being measured.

The optional attribute constraint allows for the specification of constraints imposed by this Linear Referencing Method. For example, a Reference Post Linear Referencing Method may specify that referents be of type reference marker.

The attribute positiveDistanceAlongDirection specifies the direction along the linear element being measured considered as positive used by this Linear Referencing Method. The default value is same for positive, opposite for negative.

The optional attribute measureMultiplier specifies a number which measurements obtained along the linear element being measured shall be multiplied by when using this Linear Referencing Method. This multiplier enables cases where measures with uneven distributions are needed.
The interface ISpatial is realized directly by spatial representations that also realize the ILinearElement interface.
ValueExpression is used to describe a measure value using a related Linear Referencing Method.
The attribute value gives a measure (usually a distance) of this value expression.
The interface ILinearElement is realized by all LinearElements.
The interface IFeature is realized by any feature that can be linearly measured, that is, any feature that realizes the ILinearElement interface.
LRMWithTowardsReferent extends LinearReferencingMethod by adding a subtype of Linear Referencing Method that allows towards referents, such as the Cross Street Linear Referencing Method.
The attribute type gives the type of this Linear Referencing Method. Since it supports towards referents, its type shall be relative.

The interface LRMWithOffset extends LinearReferencingMethod by adding attributes relevant to Linear Referencing Methods that allow offsets. These include units of measure and positive directions for perpendicular lateral and vertical offsets.
The attribute offsetUnits gives the units of measure used by this Linear Referencing Method for offset distances.

The attribute positiveLateralOffsetDirection gives the direction used as positive for this Linear Reference Method for lateral measures perpendicular to the base element. The default value is right for positive, left for negative.

The attribute positiveVerticalOffsetDirection gives the direction used as positive for this Linear Reference Method for vertical measures perpendicular to the base element. The default value is up for positive, down for negative.

The data type LateralOffsetDistanceExpression extends DistanceExpression, allowing the specification of lateral and vertical offsets. If either is provided, it shall include a distance measured from and perpendicular to the linear element or offset referent. The Linear Referencing Method shall be of type LRMWithOffset.

The union VerticalOffsetReferent specifies whether the vertical offset referent is a geometry of a feature or a vertical offset referent type described either as a character string or via the ICrossSectionalConventionPart interface.
Geometry used as vertical offset referent.
Description of the vertical referent to be used.
Vertical referent implemented via the ICrossSectionalConventionPart interface.

The interface ICrossSectionalConventionPart enables a standard way for human-centred denominations in specific disciplines to specify individual parts hierarchically defined in a cross-sectional position convention. A cross-sectional convention part can optionally have nested child parts. Any cross-sectional convention part can be used as lateral or vertical offset referents.
The attribute name gives the name of the cross-sectional convention part.

The enumeration VerticalOffsetDirection gives the options for positive vertical offset direction. The values are up and down. This vertical offset direction is as viewed from along the linear element facing in the direction of increasing measure. If from and towards referents have been specified, then the offset direction is as viewed from the from referent facing in the direction of the towards referent.
Positive vertical offset direction up from linear element.
Positive vertical offset direction down from linear element.

The enumeration LateralOffsetDirection gives the options for positive lateral offset direction. The values are left and right. This lateral offset direction is as viewed from above the linear element facing in the direction of increasing measure. If from and towards referents have been specified, then the offset direction is as viewed from above the from referent facing in the direction of the towards referent.
Positive lateral offset direction to the right of the linear element.
Positive lateral offset direction to the left of the linear element.

The interface ICrossSectionalConvention enables a standard way for human-centred denominations in specific disciplines to define cross-sectional position conventions. A cross-sectional position convention is typically defined hierarchically into parts, represented by the ICrossSectionalConventionPart interface. Any of these parts can be used as lateral or vertical offset referents.
The attribute name gives the name of the cross-sectional convention.

The union LateralOffsetReferent specifies whether the lateral offset referent is a geometry of a feature or a lateral offset referent type described either as a character string or via the ICrossSectionalConventionPart interface.
Geometry used as lateral offset referent.
Description of the lateral referent to be used.
Lateral referent implemented via the ICrossSectionalConventionPart interface.
The data type VerticalOffsetExpression is used to describe the vertical offset for a linearly referenced location.

The optional attribute offsetVerticalDistance is the measure of the vertical offset of the distance expression. This is the distance above or below the vertical offset referent (or, if no vertical offset referent is specified, then above or below the lateral offset referent if one is specified; otherwise, above or below the linear element being measured) to the position being specified. A positive (+) value is measured in the direction specified by the positive vertical offset direction of the LRM. A missing value or a value of 0 (zero) shall be interpreted as the absence of a vertical displacement.
The optional attribute verticalOffsetReferent indicates the base line for the vertical offset measure.
The data type LateralOffsetExpression is used to describe the lateral offset for a linearly referenced location.

The optional attribute offsetLateralDistance is the measure of the lateral offset of the distance expression. This is the distance left or right of the lateral offset referent (or left or right of the linear element being measured if no lateral offset referent is specified) to the position being specified. A positive (+) value is measured in the direction specified by the positive lateral offset direction of the LRM. A missing value or a value of 0 (zero) shall be interpreted as the absence of a lateral displacement from the lateral offset referent (or the linear element being measured if no lateral offset referent is specified).
The optional attribute lateralOffsetReferent indicates the base line for the lateral offset measure.
The data type VectorOffsetExpression is used to describe the vector offset for a linearly referenced location.

The attribute offsetVector is the offset vector of the distance expression. This specifies the distance and bearing of the offset from the linear element being measured to the position being specified. A 0 (zero) length vector shall be interpreted as not having a vector displacement from the linear element being measured.
The optional attribute vectorCRS is the offset vector Coordinate Reference System.

The data type VectorOffsetDistanceExpression extends DistanceExpression, allowing the specification of vector offsets. If provided, it shall include a vector measured from the linear element. The Linear Referencing Method shall be of type LRMWithOffset.
The data type AtLocation is used to specify a single position along the locating or attributed feature.

The attribute atPosition specifies the linearly referenced location of the event at a single point along the locating or attributed feature. A linearly referenced location defined by an PositionExpression includes the linear element being measured, a Linear Referencing Method to specify how it is measured and a distance expression to specify the measurement. For this attribute, the linear element is referenced by the Event via its linearElement role. The Linear Referencing Method is this feature's default Linear Referencing Method, unless overridden by the overridingLRM attribute of the event location. Therefore, it is sufficient to use only an DistanceExpression to specify the atPosition since a distance expression specifies the measurement.

The optional attribute overridingAtLRM specifies a Linear Referencing Method for this at location other than the default Linear Referencing Method of the locating or attributed feature being measured.
The data type EventTime is used to specify the time during which the linearly located event applies.
The data type EventPeriod is used to specify a linearly located event time which is a period of time.
The attribute duration specifies the time at which the event applies as a period of valid time.
The data type FromToLocation is used to specify a contiguous spatial interval along the locating or attributed feature.

The attribute fromPosition specifies the starting linearly referenced location of the event as a single point along the locating or attributed feature. A linearly referenced location defined by an PositionExpression includes the linear element being measured, a Linear Referencing Method to specify how it is measured and a distance expression to specify the measurement. For this attribute, the linear element is referenced by the Event via its linearElement role. The Linear Referencing Method is this feature's default Linear Referencing Method unless overridden by the overridingLRM attribute of the event location. Therefore, it is sufficient to use only an DistanceExpression to specify the fromPosition since a distance expression specifies the measurement.

The optional attribute overridingFromLRM specifies a Linear Referencing Method for this from/to location other than the default Linear Referencing Method of the locating or attributed feature being measured.

The attribute toPosition specifies the ending linearly referenced location of the event as a single point along the locating or attributed feature. A linearly referenced location defined by an PositionExpression includes the linear element being measured, a Linear Referencing Method to specify how it is measured and a distance expression to specify the measurement. For this attribute, the linear element is referenced by the Event via its linearElement role. The Linear Referencing Method is this feature's default Linear Referencing Method unless overridden by the overridingLRM attribute of the event location. Therefore, it is sufficient to use only an DistanceExpression to specify the toPosition since a distance expression specifies the measurement.

The optional attribute overridingToLRM specifies a Linear Referencing Method for this from/to location other than the default Linear Referencing Method of the locating or attributed feature being measured.
The data type EventLocation is used to specify the linearly referenced location of a linearly located event along a locating or attributed feature.

The Event interface is used to specify information about linearly located feature and attribute events, the linear location along which the event applies, defined by linearly referenced locations along the Linear Element and possibly further qualified as applying at an instant in, or during a period of, time.
The attribute eventName specifies the name of the event.

The attribute location specifies the linearly referenced location for this event.
A single event instance occurs only in a single place. However, this single place may be described by both at and from/To locations.
The optional attribute time specifies the time during which the event applies.

The AttributeEvent interface is used to specify information about linearly located attribute events. This information includes an event name and a value specifying an attribute value applicable to the attribute feature, the linear location along which the event applies, defined by linearly referenced locations along a LinearElement and possibly further qualified as applying at an instant in, or during a period of, time.
The attribute value specifies the value of the event being located. The data type of value is ANY.
The type EventInstant is used to specify a linearly located event time which is a single instant in time.
The attribute atTime specifies the time at which the event applies as a single instant in valid time.
The FeatureEvent interface is used to linearly reference a feature along a LinearElement and possibly further qualified as applying at an instant in, or during a period of, time.
The interface LinearSegmentSet defines the set of linear segments that results from a single execution of the segment operation on a SegmentableFeature.
The attribute eventName specifies the name of the attribute event(s) that were used to generate this linear segment set. The eventName is the eventName of the Event.
The type SegmentableFeature is extended from IFeature with the segmentation operation and output.
The interface LinearSegment is used to specify the individual linear segments that result from the execution of the segment operation on a Feature.

The attribute startFeatureLocation specifies the linearly referenced location along the segmented feature where the generated linear segment begins. A linearly referenced location defined by a PositionExpression includes the linear element being measured, a Linear Referencing Method to specify how it is measured and a distance expression to specify the measurement. For this attribute, the linear element is the segmented feature. The Linear Referencing Method is this feature's default Linear Referencing Method. Therefore, it is sufficient to use only an DistanceExpression to specify the startFeatureLocation since a distance expression specifies the measurement.
The attribute endFeatureLocation specifies the linearly referenced location along the segmented feature where the generated linear segment ends.
The attribute segmentingAttributeValue specifies the value of an attribute of this linear segment.
